summary: Idk if this counts but I have a friend of mine who is fat, and male, and he loved endgame because as much as there’s a few lines...
question: Idk if this counts but I have a friend of mine who is fat, and male, and he loved endgame because as much as there’s a few lines about how he needs to have salad or something, Thor is still a badass while fat. Like he still almost defeated Thanos, and was fat, and didn’t have a training montage to become thin again, and that’s why he liked it.
answer: Those are good points, and I’m glad he liked it! Obviously not everyone has to feel the same way about it as me. And it is super awesome that Thor kicked ass without having to lose weight. I don’t think I made this clear in my original post, but I’m all for Thor being fat. I just think it’s frustrating, and says a lot about the state of fat representation, that Thor being a badass had to be surrounded by people making disparaging comments about his weight and diet throughout the movie. Also just the way his weight gain is framed…it’s not respectful at all, and I think clearly meant as a joke. So while I really am glad your friend enjoyed seeing Thor in this movie, and I did overlook how much his portrayal probably meant to people, I still think the movie could’ve done a much better job of handling Thor’s whole plot line with respect instead of resorting to fatphobia for humor.

summary: x weeks into avengers: endgame and - @ the people sobbing, sobbing intensely and then chuckling through tears: i hear you. i...
body:
x weeks into avengers: endgame and -

@ the people sobbing, sobbing intensely and then chuckling through tears: i hear you. i feel you.

i still think the final stand sequence is peak poetic cinema/one of the best things to ever exist. wholesome, cinematic, art, a masterpiece.

95% of the time i forget that rocket is a cgi character.

my girl wanda would’ve teared the purple grape into pieces, goddamn! i hope the show and future mcu movies really get to show how powerful she is.

2014!thanos always waits as someone else gets him the stones. he waited in 616′s 2014, and waits in 2023 as he sends off nebula to get him the gauntlet. 2014 THANOS ALWAYS WAITS!

someone on here called bucky ‘sad barbie’ a million days ago and now i can’t unsee it.
i also cannot wait to see bucky’s and sam’s looks for the show. also, the plot. also, the actual show and how, if at all, it ties up to future mcu movies. i also cannot wait to find out why the black widow movie is the first movie of phase 4 and the first movie of the new saga/era - these things don’t just randomly happen in the mcu, there’s always a reason, and damn am i excited. i’m so excited for the future of the mcu.

summary: Avengers Endgame: Male Entitlement Undermines Steve Rogers' Core Characterization and Story Arc - Cinemalogue
body:
Avengers Endgame: Male Entitlement Undermines Steve Rogers’ Core Characterization and Story Arc - Cinemalogue

This. This. THIS!

“Never in any previous comic, any previous Marvel property, any iteration of the character, has Steve Rogers ever returned to the past and stayed there.  It would be contrary to who he is.  Steve always gets up again.  He choses the harder right over the easier wrong.  He always looks forward, head up.  He never runs away from a fight.  Never would he leave a world recovering from a collective, apocalyptic trauma to go live in a Cold War-era domestic ‘utopia’, least of all at the expense of his paramour’s agency.”
